markdown_instructions.U3L26 NOT operator_markdown_instruction:
## NOT Operator

The NOT operator can be used to reverse a boolean statement. If a statements true, the NOT operator will evaluate to false. If the statement is false, the NOT operator will evaluate to true. The NOT operator looks like "!" in JavaScript.

<details>
<summary>**Example**</summary>
<pre>`if (!contains(sentence, "word1")) {
	setText("text_area", "Word1 is not in the sentence!");
} else {
	setText("text_area", "Word1 is in the sentence!");
}`</pre>
</details>

<details>
<summary>**Where is the NOT block?**</summary>
![](https://images.code.org/85c2de713a94c930611c0fd6afeaf3d6-image-1438876242202.gif)
</details>

### Instructions

Movie Bot helps people find the most popular movies.

* Write a conditional statement that detects if a command does not contain the phrase "bad"
* If "bad" is not detected, make Movie Bot respond normally. Otherwise, make Movie Bot say "Sorry, I don't know about bad movies."

